          "body": "Amos's reply to Amaziah (7:14-15) is one of the most carefully constructed self-defenses in prophetic literature, and its argument runs entirely counter to what Amaziah expects. Amaziah has framed the dispute as institutional: Amos is a Judean professional who has no business prophesying in Israel's official sanctuary. Amos does not counter with credentials; he counters with a commission. 'I am not a prophet, nor am I the son of a prophet' — he belongs to no guild, no school, no professional class. He owes nothing to the northern religious establishment, cannot be dismissed from it, and cannot be bribed or threatened through it. 'But the Lord took me from following the flock and the Lord said to me, Go prophesy to My people Israel' (7:15). The authority is not Amos's own; it was conferred by a specific divine act of taking and commanding. This is the Old Testament parallel to the apostolic 'we cannot but speak' (Acts 4:20). When God has specifically taken a person and spoken a specific commission, no institutional authority can revoke it."
